===Etymology===
[[File:Vrba postelja.jpg|thumb|right|A bed (furniture)]]

From {{inh|en|enm|bed}}, {{m|enm|bedde}}, from {{inh|en|ang|bedd|t=bed, couch, resting-place; garden-bed, plot}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*badją||plot, grave, resting-place, bed}}, perhaps (if originally "dug sleeping-place") from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰedʰh₂-|*bʰedʰ-|t=to dig}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|bed}}, {{m|sco|bede||bed}}, {{cog|frr|baad}}, {{m|frr|beed||bed}}, {{cog|fy|bêd||bed}}, {{cog|nds|Bedd}}, {{cog|nl|bed||bed}}, {{cog|de|Bett||bed}}, {{cog|da|bed}}, {{cog|sv|bädd||bed}}, {{cog|is|beður||bed}}, and (through {{der|en|ine-pro|-}}, if the above etymology is correct) with {{cog|grc|βοθυρος||pit}}, {{cog|la|fossa||ditch}}, {{cog|lv|bedre||hole}}, {{cog|cy|bedd||grave}}, {{cog|br|bez||grave}}; and probably also {{cog|ru|бодать||to butt, to gore}}.

The traditional etymology as a derivation from the Proto-Indo-European verb for 'to dig' has been doubted, arguing that there are (allegedly) few, if any, cultures known to dig out beds, rather than to build "pads". However, what the Germanic word originally referred to is not known with precision, and it notably has the additional meaning "flower-bed, plot", which is preserved in English and several other modern Germanic languages, but present in older stages as well. Additionally, the term may have originally been used in the sense of a "burial plot" for laying those who were asleep in death, and from there extended also to symbolise a place where one slept in general (In Modern German, two separate words exist, ''Bett'' being the normal term, the rare variant {{m|de|Beet}} having been adopted for “flower-bed”). Perhaps the word originally referred to dug sleeping-places of animals, compare (with the inverse semantic development) {{m|en|lair}} from {{cog|ang|leġer||couch, bed}}.

